ce:section.ce:para:
It is essential to discriminate the effect of different pH on GQDs before sensing studies. The influence of pH on the fluorescent properties of PAsP-GQDs was also investigated. A stable fluorescence was observed at a pH of 7.4. Besides, the decline in intensity was noted at highly acidic pH and in basic pH. The stability of fluorescence of PAsP-GQDs is estimated also in different solvents, including ethanol, methanol, IPA, DMSO, EG, DI water and PBS (pH 7.4). A very slight change in the fluorescent intensity of the PAsP-GQDs was noted that signifies the stability of PAsP-GQDs in various solvents as well as its better stability in PBS (pH 7.4) ( Fig. 2 -f, and S1, a-b) [41,42]. The surface interactions with different interfering elements such as ions (Fe+, Na+, K+, Ca+) and other organic compounds solutions (ascorbic acid, lactose, urea, folic acid, glucose,) were examined to assist the effect of various physiological conditions on PAsP-GQDs. These interfering elements had a negligible effect on the fluorescent intensity of the PAsP-GQDs (
Figure S2
).

The surface charge is essential for the assessment of the sensing reaction between PAsP-GQDs and the other reacting components. Thus, the zeta (ζ) potential of the ONI-GQDs and PAsP-GQDs was carried out. The ζ-potential ONI-GQDs were observed at about −13.2 mV and that of the PAsP-GQDs at 39.4 mV (
Figure S4
). The HRTEM analysis of PAsP-GQDs revealed the average particle size around ∼ 9.1 nm with an interatomic distance of 0.19 nm (d-spacing). The selected area diffraction (SAED) showed the polycrystalline nature of PAsP-GQDs ( Fig. 3 , a-b).

The onion hull components under hydrothermal treatment converts in turbostratic carbon phase followed by rearranged in graphitic carbon structures. The PXRD analysis of PAsP-GQDs showed a peak at 2θ = 22.6° and 28.6° (d002 = 0.19) of turbostratic phase (ONI-GQDs). Besides, typical peaks at 2θ = 17.7° and 44.2 resembles typical peaks (004) and (002) of graphite elements (
Figure S5
) [37,46,47].

It is essential to assess whether the MAGE-11 immunosensor has selectivity towards MAGE-11 or not. Thus, different interfering other proteins/biomarkers (CEA, hTERT, Egg albumin, CD59 antigen, BSA, and glucose, glucosamine, ascorbic acid, each 0.1 µg mL−1) were established with MAGE-11-Ag (0.5 ng mL−1) to realize whether the expected method is specific for MAGE-11-Ag sensing or not (

                           Figure S7

                        ).

Subsequently, the reproducibility of the prepared PAsP-GQDs@M−A11−Ab sensor was tested by fabricating four same immunosensor (namely, MA-11-Ab@GQDs-1, anti- MA-11-Ab@GQDs-2 and MA-11-Ab@GQDs-3, MA-11-Ab@GQDs-4) executing a similar method with 0.5 ng mL−1 MAGE-A11 concentration with GrN as a quencher. The recovery in fluorescence from these four immunosensors was calculated from equation (4) which was noted about 98.8 % with a percentage RSD of 1.27 and marginal changes in intensity were noted (1.7 %) which suggests a remarkable reproducibility of the immunosensor (

                           Figure S9

                        ).
